IRQBALANCE(1) irqbalance IRQBALANCE(1)
[1mNAME[0m irqbalance - distribute hardware interrupts across processors on a multiprocessor system
[1mSYNOPSIS[0m [1mirqbalance[0m
[1mDESCRIPTION[0m The purpose of [1mirqbalance[0m is distribute hardware interrupts across processors on a multiprocessor system in order to increase performance.
[1mOPTIONS[0m [1m--oneshot[0m Causes irqbalance to be run once, after which the daemon exits
[1m--debug[0m Causes irqbalance to print extra debug information. Implies --foreground
[1m--foreground[0m Causes irqbalance to run in the foreground (without --debug)
[1m--hintpolicy=[exact[0m [1m|[0m [1msubset[0m [1m|[0m [1mignore][0m Set the policy for how irq kernel affinity hinting is treated. Can be one of:
[4mexact[24m irq affinity hint is applied unilaterally and never violated
[4msubset[24m irq is balanced, but the assigned object will be a subset of the affintiy hint
[4mignore[24m

irq affinity hint value is completely ignored
[1m--powerthresh=<threshold>[0m Set the threshold at which we attempt to move a cpu into powersave mode If more than <threshold> cpus are more than 1 standard deviation below the average cpu softirq workload, and no cpus are more than 1 standard deviation above (and have more than 1 irq assigned to them), attempt to place 1 cpu in powersave mode. In powersave mode, a cpu will not have any irqs balanced to it, in an effort to prevent that cpu from waking up without need.
[1m--banirq=<irqnum>[0m Add the specified irq to the set of banned irqs. irqbalance will not affect the affinity of any irqs on the banned list, allowing them to be specified manually. This option is addative and can be specified multiple times. For example to ban irqs 43 and 44 from balancing, use the following command line: [1mirqbalance[0m [1m--banirq=43[0m [1m--banirq=44[0m
[1m--policyscript=<script>[0m When specified, the referenced script will execute once for each discovered irq, with the sysfs device path and irq number passed as arguments. The script may specify zero or more key=value pairs that will guide irqbalance in the management of that irq. Key=value pairs are printed by the script on stdout and will be captured and interpreted by irqbalance. Irqbalance expects a zero exit code from the provided utility. Recognized key=value pairs are:
[4mban=[true[24m [4m|[24m [4mfalse][24m
Directs irqbalance to exclude the passed in irq from balancing
[4mbalance_level=[none[24m [4m|[24m [4mpackage[24m [4m|[24m [4mcache[24m [4m|[24m [4m

core][24m This allows a user to override the balance level of a given irq. By default the balance level is determined automatically based on the pci device class of the device that owns the irq.
[4mnuma_node=<integer>[24m This allows a user to override the numa node that sysfs indicates a given device irq is local to. Often, systems will not specify this information in ACPI, and as a result devicesa are con sidered equidistant from all numa nodes in a system. This option allows for that hardware provided information to be overridden, so that irqbalance can bias irq affinity for these devices toward its most local node. Note that specifying a -1 here forces irqbalance to consider an interrupt from a device to be equidistant from all nodes.
[1m--pid=<file>[0m Have irqbalance write its process id to the specified file. By default no pidfile is written. The written pidfile is automatically unlinked when irqbalance exits. [7m Manual page irqbalance(1) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)[27m[K
